properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Tallangatta Creek. 

MAJOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MCCALLUMS DURING MONDAY EVENING
River levels are rising along the Tallangatta Creek with major flooding occurring.
Showers and thunderstorms are forecast during Monday evening into Tuesday.

Tallangatta Creek: 
Major flooding is occurring along the Tallangatta Creek. The river level at McCallums is currently at 2.56 metres and rising (major flood level 2.30 m).
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.

If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.

If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.

Impacts in your area:

  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.   
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams. 
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides â€“ be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 11:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Mitta Mitta River upstream of Lake Dartmouth .

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT TALLANDOON DURING TUESDAY MORNING AND MCCALLUMS DURING MONDAY AFTERNOON 

River levels remain elevated along the Mitta Mitta River. 
At Tallandoon river level rises are being observed just below the minor flood level. 

Minor flooding is likely to develop from Monday afternoon, with moderate flooding possible from Tuesday morning.
River levels are rising along the Tallangatta Creek with minor flooding occurring and further rises likely during Monday.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am 20-35 mm of rainfall totals have been observed across the catchment. Rainfall totals of 25-50mm have been forecast during Monday with higher isolated totals possible.The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Mitta Mitta River upstream of Lake Dartmouth: 
River levels are steady along the Mitta Mitta River upstream of Lake Dartmouth at Hinnomunjie. 
Forecast rainfall is likely to cause renewed river level rises from Monday evening. 

Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth:
Moderate flooding may occur along the Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth.The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is currently at 4.13 metres and rising. The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.20 m) Monday afternoon. The river level may reach the moderate flood level (4.90 m) Tuesday morning with forecast rainfall.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Tanjiil River.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon.

 Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.

In parts of the North East and far East Gippsland, isolated major flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday.

Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

Latrobe River
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
Moderate Flood Warning for the Goulburn River

Moderate flooding may occur along the Acheron River.

The Acheron River at Taggerty is currently at 2.14 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. Renewed rises are likely along the Acheron River at Taggerty during Monday, with forecast rainfall. The river level may reach the minor flood level from Monday evening, with further rises to the moderate flood level possible overnight.

Forecast rainfall during Monday and Tuesday is expected to see renewed river level rises throughout the Goulburn River catchment, with prolonged or renewed minor to moderate flooding.

Updated Community information: 
  • Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.
  • Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick. 
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  

Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.  Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.   

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Castle Creek.

Castle Creek:
River levels have eased below the minor flood level along the Castle Creek. Renewed rises may occur during Monday evening and into Tuesday with forecast rainfall but river levels are likely to remain below the minor flood level.

Updated Community information:

Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases. 

 Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.     

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures go to traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River to Charlton Town.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Avoca River to Charlton Town.

  • The Avoca River at Charlton Township is currently at 4.16m and steady, with minor flooding. The Avoca River at Charlton Township is likely to remain above the minor flood level (4.00m) overnight Monday into Tuesday.
In the 24 hours to 12:00 pm Monday, rainfall totals of less than 5mm were recorded in the Avoca River catchment. Forecast rainfall over the next few days is likely to see renewed river level rises across the Avoca River catchment.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au
  • For more information on road closures check the VicTraffic
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Bunyip River downstream of Iona.

The Bunyip River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 1 mm since 09:00 AM Sunday 30 October 2022. The Western Port catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 0 mm for the same period. Rainfall totals of 10-20 mm are forecast for the catchment on Monday 31 October 2022, with thunderstorms and isolated totals of 30-40 mm possible.

Bunyip River downstream of Iona:
The level of the Bunyip River at Cora Lynn is currently at 3.26 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.10 metres), and falling. If the rainfall occurs as forecast the level is expected to peak again above the Minor Flood Level (3.10 metres) on Wednesday morning 02 November 2022. The river level is expected to remain above the Minor Flood Level (3.10 metres) until Friday 05 November 2022.

Minor flooding in the Bunyip River catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway. The ford at Cora Lynn is closed to traffic.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause renewed river rises across the Latrobe River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Minor flooding is occurring along the Latrobe River downstream of Traralgon.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Snowy River to McKillops Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING CONTINUING AT MCKILLOPS BRIDGE

RENEWED RIVER LEVEL RISES ARE LIKELY WITH FORECAST RAINFALL FROM MONDAY EVENING

In the 48 hours to 3:00 pm Monday, no significant rainfall totals have been recorded in the Snowy River catchment. Rainfall forecast for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause renewed river rises across the Buchan, Bombala and Snowy River catchments. 

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Snowy River to McKillops Bridge:

Minor flooding is occurring along the Snowy River to McKillops Bridge. Snowy Hydro advise Jindabyne is fulland spilling.

The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is currently at 2.78 metres and steady, with minor flooding. The Snowy River at McKillops Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (2.50 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday. Renewed river level rises are likely from Monday evening .
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides â€“ be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
  • Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

Accessibility:

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Seven Creeks to Euroa

RENEWED RISES TO THE MINOR FLOOD LEVEL LIKELY AT EUROA FROM MONDAY EVENING.

River levels are currently below the minor flood level along the Seven Creeks to Euroa. Renewed rises are expected during Monday with areas of minor flooding likely from Monday evening. The Seven Creeks at Euroa is currently at 2.30 metres and easing, below the minor flood level. Renewed rises are expected during Monday and the Seven Creeks at Euroa is likely to exceed the minor flood level (2.50 m) early Monday evening. River levels are likely to remain above the minor flood level into Tuesday

Updated Community information: 

Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases. 

 Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   

Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.     

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one.
When returning home 
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property.  
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask.  
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.  
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.  
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760

Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and flooding may still affect areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may still be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Low lying caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.

This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery: 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support 
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Portland Coast Catchment.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON
  • A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. 
  • The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday. 
  • Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday. 
  • Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 
  • Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.
  • Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.
  • Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 
  • Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message has been issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek..

  • A landslide has occurred in the Bogong High Plains Road above Bogong Village.
  • There is a large active slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village.
  • After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the tack onto Bogong High Plains Road.
  • Further rainfall and snow are forecast which could increase movement of the landslide.
  • Emergency services are in progress of building alternative access for emergency service. This track is not currently safe for use.

  • The Bogong High Plains Road is closed from Mount Beauty to Falls Creek to all traffic - until further notice, and will not reopen until deemed safe. 

  • An exclusion zone has been established, prohibiting entry into the area defined in the map which is available at Bogong Landslip - Exclusion Zone. Access to this area is strictly prohibited and is a treat to your life if you entre. 
 
Avoid the area. Stay clear of fallen earth and trees, blocked or damaged roads. Be aware or other hazards caused by the landslip. Do not enter the exclusion zone.
What you should do:
  • Stay away from the impacted area.
  • If another landslide occurs, act quickly.
  • If you are outside when a landslide occurs, move quickly and keep clear of embankments, trees, power lines and poles. 
  • If you are inside, move to the part of the building that is furthers away from the the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
Travelling
  • Plan you trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads ad poor driving conditions.
  • There will be no public access to Falls Creek and Bogong Village as the Bogong High Plains Road remains closed.
  • The Bogong High Plains Road south of Falls Creek is open to local traffic only, accessible via the Omeo Highway. 
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.

properties.text: ADVICE - LANDSLIDE Incident Location: Bogong Village and Falls Creek Issue Date: Monday 31 October 2022, 03:45 pm Next Update: Monday 07 November 2022, 05:00 pm More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25704/moreinfo This Advice message has been issued for Bogong Village and Falls Creek.. - A landslide has occurred in the Bogong High Plains Road above Bogong Village. - There is a large active slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village. - After recent heavy rainfall, cracking has been identified in the area around Spring Saddle Track and debris has been moving from below the tack onto Bogong High Plains Road. - Further rainfall and snow are forecast which could increase movement of the landslide. - Emergency services are in progress of building alternative access for emergency service. This track is not currently safe for use. - The Bogong High Plains Road is closed from Mount Beauty to Falls Creek to all traffic - until further notice, and will not reopen until deemed safe. - An exclusion zone has been established, prohibiting entry into the area defined in the map which is available at Bogong Landslip - Exclusion Zone. Access to this area is strictly prohibited and is a treat to your life if you entre. Avoid the area. Stay clear of fallen earth and trees, blocked or damaged roads. Be aware or other hazards caused by the landslip. Do not enter the exclusion zone.

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.

In parts of the North East and far East Gippsland, isolated flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday.

properties.name: Advice
properties.webBody:
This Advice message is being issued for Lakes Entrance.

  • Due to a whale carcass at the beach, which was first located last week, there could be an increase in shark activity.
  • A whale carcass can attract sharks to the area and mean they are closer to the shore than normal.
  • While it is not uncommon for sharks to be present off the Victorian coast, you should exercise additional caution in the area.
  • The carcass was originally located in Marlo, but as of 21/10/2022, it has broken up and spread out along the coast between Lake Tyers Beach and Lakes Entrance.
  • This is an update, replacing the Advice issued on Monday at 3.15pm.
Avoid the area. Stay informed and do not enter the water at closed beaches.
What you should do:

  • If you see sharks, report the sighting by calling Triple Zero (000) or notify lifesavers immediately if you are at a patrolled beach.
Staying safe at nearby beaches:
  • Always swim, dive or surf with a friend.
  • Swim between the red and yellow flags on patrolled beaches.
  • Don't swim in places where human or animal waste enters the water.
  • Keep away from large schools of fish, seals or other wildlife as these can attract sharks.
Impacts in your area:
  • The Victorian Fisheries Authority is monitoring for shark sightings and providing advice to relevant authorities. 
This message was issued by VFA.

The next update is expected by 02/11/2022 11:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT WANGARATTA AND DOCKER RD BRIDGE RENEWED FLOODING IS LIKELY IN THE OVENS AND KING RIVERS FROM MONDAY EVENING

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Road Bridge and has extended along the Ovens River at Wangaratta. Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Downstream (D/S) Lake William Hovell, and the Ovens River at Rocky Point. 

Renewed river rises are occurring along parts of the Ovens and King rivers and renewed flooding is likely from Monday evening. 

Renewed minor flooding is expected along the Buffalo River at Downstream (D/S) Lake Buffalo from early Monday evening.

Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause further river level rises and prolong the duration of flooding throughout the Ovens and King catchments.

Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point:
Moderate flooding is occurring along the Ovens River downstream of Rocky Point.
The Ovens River at Wangaratta peaked at 15.52 metres around midday Sunday and is currently at 12.47 metres and falling slowly, with moderate flooding. The Ovens River at Wangaratta is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (12.40 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday. Renewed rises may occur from early Tuesday morning.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • A number of local roads and may be closed due to flooding.
At the Minor Flood Level (11.9m):
  • Water up to Yogi's chin in Apex Park
  • Apex Park and farmland along the Ovens, King and possibly the Fifteen Mile Creek floodplains north, south and east of Wangaratta may begin flooding
  • Bike paths and walking tracks around and downstream of Apex Park and the Northern Beaches may be closed
  • Many riverside carparks may be closed including Sydney Beach, Bickerton St and Baker St
  • The Great Alpine Road at East Wangaratta is closed due to flooding, with detours in place

At the Moderate Flood Level (12.4m):
  • Extensive flooding through APEX Park, water up to Yogi's mouth
  • Bickerton St carpark will be closed and the access road to Painters Island Caravan Park flooded
  • Shallow flooding to Pinkerton Cres and backyards along Templeton St and Baker St

The following roads may be affected by flooding as the river level rises and may be closed:
  • The Great Alpine Road, East Wangaratta
  • Peechelba Road (East of the Ovens River)
  • Wilson Road (outside of the levee protected area)
  • Markwood-Everton Road
  • Bickerton Street, including the car parking areas
  • Milawa-Tarrawingee Road
  • College Street, preventing access to the Northern Beaches carpark
  • Markwood-Tarrawingee Road
  • Pinkerton Crescent
  • Baker Street car park
  • Dowling Lane River Road
  • Oxley Flats Road
  • Stamps Lane / Dale Street / Ambrosio Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

This Flood Watch is being issued for Hughes Creek.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.
Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 
Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.
Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 
Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.

 Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.

Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.
Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.   
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area:

properties.location: the Goulburn River Lake Eildon and at Seymour
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River Lake Eildon and at Seymour.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, TRAWOOL AND SEYMOUR

Moderate flooding is peaking at Trawool around 5.89 metres (moderate flood level 5.60 m).The Goulburn River D/S Lake Eildon is currently at 4.39 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Goulburn River D/S Lake Eildon is likely to remain steady around 4.40 metres during the next few days.

The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 5.84 metres and peaking, with moderate flooding. The Goulburn River at Seymour is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (5.20 m) during Monday and into Tuesday.

  • Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon are around 30,000 ML/d and will remain around this flow for the next few days
  • Forecast rainfall during Monday and Tuesday is expected to see renewed river level rises throughout the Goulburn River catchment, with prolonged or renewed minor to moderate flooding.
  • The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
COMMUNTITY INFORMATION
  • Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.
  • Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. 
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  
Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding.

Do not camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend!

Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam. Your access tracks in and out might be flooded and you might end up stranded for days.

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.

What you should do:

  • Check out the Seymour Local Flood guide or the Mitchell Shire Flood Emergency Plan for more detailed flood information and maps https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/mitchell-shire-council
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground, if not already done and is safe to.
  • Be prepared to move household items to higher ground, on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds. 
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes, medications and scripts (prescriptions) with you.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • GMW Water are releasing water from Lake Eildon to control the rate the storage is filling and make room for further inflows.  
  • GMW advises â€œIt is important people who live or farm on floodplains have their properties prepared for any potential flood events. This includes ensuring there are no flaws with any dams on their properties and having a plan to move livestock and equipment to higher ground".
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home and sheds, garages etc is likely to occur in some locations.
  • A small number of properties are likely to be impacted and possibility become isolated.
In Seymour, at the predicted 5.2 m (Moderate flood level): 
  • Tierney, High and Wallis Streets start to flood. 
  • Emily Street stormwater backs up around roads and gardens. 
  • Goulburn River Caravan Park likely to re-activate their evacuation plan
From minor flood level (4.0m), Kings Park, three of the local caravan parks and farmland along the Old Hume Highway start to flood. Seymour stormwater drainage commences overflowing.
  • the Goulburn River breaks its banks causing flooding on low-lying farmland, parkland, low-lying roads and river crossings. 

  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • You may lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Fishing, kayaking, Boating in floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

WATCH & ACT - RIVERINE FLOOD - Prepare Now
Incident Location: the Goulburn River Lake Eildon to Seymour
Issue Date: Monday 31 October 2022, 11:59 am
Next Update: Tuesday 01 November 2022, 12:00 pm

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25650/moreinfo


This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Goulburn River Lake Eildon and at Seymour.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM LAKE EILDON, TRAWOOL AND SEYMOUR 

Moderate flooding is peaking at Trawool around 5.89 metres (moderate flood level 5.60 m).The Goulburn River D/S Lake Eildon is currently at 4.39 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. The Goulburn River D/S Lake Eildon is likely to remain steady around 4.40 metres during the next few days.

The Goulburn River at Seymour is currently at 5.84 metres and peaking, with moderate flooding. The Goulburn River at Seymour is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (5.20 m) during Monday and into Tuesday. 

- Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon are around 30,000 ML/d and will remain around this flow for the next few days 
- Forecast rainfall during Monday and Tuesday is expected to see renewed river level rises throughout the Goulburn River catchment, with prolonged or renewed minor to moderate flooding. 
- The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

COMMUNTITY INFORMATION
- Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.
- Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.
- In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. 
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  

Prepare for flooding now. Take actions to protect your life and property against potential hazards caused by flooding. 

Do not camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend!

Unexpected and rapid river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon dam. Your access tracks in and out might be flooded and you might end up stranded for days.

Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters (ABC or UGFM radio) via your car radio if necessary.

This Flood Watch is being issued for the Buckland River.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON   

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. 
The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.    

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.   Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 

Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.   
Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 

Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.  

In parts of the North East with isolated major flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday.   
Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.   

A minor to major flood warning is current for the Murray River.   
 
Moderate flood warnings are current Ovens and King, Goulburn, Mitta Mitta Rivers and the Murray River upstream of Lake Hume.   

Minor flood warnings are current for the Kiewa, the Broken, Seven and Castle Creeks.  
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 1 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 1 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Sunday 30 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 10-20 mm are forecast for the catchment on Monday 31 October 2022, with thunderstorms and isolated totals of 30-40 mm possible.

Yarra River from Coldstream to Warrandyte:

The level of the Yarra River at Yarra Glen is currently steady at 4.62 metres, exceeding the Moderate Flood Level (4.60 metres). It is expected to drop below the Moderate Flood Level on Monday afternoon (31 October 2022), and below the Minor flood Level (4.1 metres) on Sunday 6 November 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Christmas Hills is currently at 3.41 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) and falling. It peaked at 3.95 metres at 8:00 PM Saturday 29 October 2022, and is expected to drop below the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres) on Thursday 03 November 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Warrandyte is currently at 3.59 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres), and falling. It peaked at 4.2 metres at 2:00 AM Sunday 30 October 2022, and is expected to drop below Minor Flood level (3.00 metres) on Tuesday 02 November 2022. 

Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded.

  • This is an update, replacing the Watch and Act message issued at 8:58 PM on the 30/10/2022. 
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.

Roads that may be impacted by flooding of the Yarra River in Yarra Glen include: 
  • The Healesville-Yarra Glen road, between Bell Street and Yarra Valley Racecourse and between the Melba Highway and the Yarra Glen Bypass. 
  • Armstrong Grove 
  • Bell Street 
  • Yarraview Road
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 09:30 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Otway Coast.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON
  • A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. 
  • The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.
  • Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday. 
  • Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 
  • Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.
  • Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.
  • Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 
  • Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong.

MINOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT BRINGENBRONG AND JINGELLIC IN THE NEXT FEW HOURS RISES TO THE MODERATE FLOOD LEVEL LIKELY AT BRINGENBRONG OVERNIGHT MONDAY AND AT JINGELLIC TUESDAY EVENING

River level rises are occurring across the catchment with minor flooding expected in the next few hours. Further rainfall is forecast for Monday and Tuesday and is likely to cause further rises and areas of moderate flooding.
Snowy Hydro advise that the releases from Khancoban Pondage are currently at the minor flood level and increasing into Monday night.

Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong: 
Moderate flooding is likely along the Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong from overnight Monday. 
The Murray River at Bringenbrong is currently at 2.87 metres and steady. 
The Murray River at Bringenbrong is expected to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) early Monday afternoon. 

The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (3.40 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday and may peak near 3.45 metres overnight Monday into Tuesday. Moderate flood levels are likely to continue into Tuesday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 10:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
The Bureau of Meteorology has issued a Severe Weather Warning for people in parts of East Gippsland and North East Forecast Districts.

  • This Advice message is for damaging winds.
  • Damaging northwesterly winds, averaging 50 to 65 km/h with peak gusts of 90 to 100 km/h are forecast in the warning area over the next few hours.
  • Gusts may reach 100 to 110 km/h over the alpine region.
  • Severe thunderstorms remain possible in the northeast of the state early this evening and may further enhance the risk of severe wind gusts.
  • Saturated soils bring an increased risk of gusty winds toppling trees and powerlines.
  • Winds are expected to ease below warning criteria this evening.
  • This Advice replaces the Advice message issued at 11:28am Monday 31 October.
Stay informed and be aware of potential hazards caused by severe weather. Hazards include falling trees and powerlines. 
What you should do:
  • Park your car undercover and away from trees.
  • Stay inside if conditions outside appear dangerous.
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so.
  • When preparing your property, ensure you take appropriate safety precautions and do so well before the severe weather arrives.
  • Be aware of hazardous trees - recent rainfall may make trees unstable and more likely to fall during a storm.

If you are driving:
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater.
  • Be aware of road hazards such as mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Drive slowly and obey all road signs. Never drive through floodwater.
  • For road closure information, check the VicTraffic website, contact your local council or call VicRoads (13 11 70).

You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.

Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. For severe weather related emergency assistance from the SES, phone 132 500.
Impacts in your area:
The potential impacts of severe weather in your area include:
  • Fallen power lines
  • Fallen trees and branches
  • Damage to vehicles
  • Dangerous road conditions
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

More details at http://emergency.vic.gov.au/respond/#!/warning/25748/moreinfo

The Bureau of Meteorology has issued a Severe Weather Warning for people in parts of East Gippsland and North East Forecast Districts.

- This Advice message is for damaging winds.
- Damaging northwesterly winds, averaging 50 to 65 km/h with peak gusts of 90 to 100 km/h are forecast in the warning area over the next few hours. 
- Gusts may reach 100 to 110 km/h over the alpine region. 
- Severe thunderstorms remain possible in the northeast of the state early this evening and may further enhance the risk of severe wind gusts. 
- Saturated soils bring an increased risk of gusty winds toppling trees and powerlines. 
- Winds are expected to ease below warning criteria this evening.
- This Advice replaces the Advice message issued at 11:28am Monday 31 October.


Stay informed and be aware of potential hazards caused by severe weather. Hazards include falling trees and powerlines.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Murray River upstream of Lake Hume.

MINOR FLOODING EXPECTED AT BRINGENBRONG AND JINGELLIC IN THE NEXT FEW HOURS RISES TO THE MODERATE FLOOD LEVEL LIKELY AT BRINGENBRONG OVERNIGHT MONDAY AND AT JINGELLIC TUESDAY EVENING

River level rises are occurring across the catchment with minor flooding expected in the next few hours. Further rainfall is forecast for Monday and Tuesday and is likely to cause further rises and areas of moderate flooding.
Snowy Hydro advise that the releases from Khancoban Pondage are currently at the minor flood level and increasing into Monday night.

Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong:
Moderate flooding is likely along the Murray River Biggara to Bringenbrong from overnight Monday.
The Murray River at Bringenbrong is currently at 2.87 metres and steady. The Murray River at Bringenbrongis expected to exceed the minor flood level (3.00 m) early Monday afternoon. 
The river level is likely to exceed the moderate flood level (3.40 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday and may peak near 3.45 metres overnight Monday into Tuesday. Moderate flood levels are likely to continue into Tuesday.

Murray River Bringenbrong to Lake Hume:
Minor flooding may develop along the Murray River Bringenbrong to Lake Hume with further rises to the moderate flood level.
The Murray River at Jingellic is currently at 3.94 metres and rising slowly, just below the minor flood level(4.00 metres). 
The Murray River at Jingellic is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.00 m) early Monday afternoon. 

Further rises are expected later Monday and into Tuesday where river levels may reach the moderate flood level (5.50 m) Tuesday evening.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 10:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
