properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton

Minor flooding is occurring along the Goulburn River downstream of Shepparton.

The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is currently at 9.74 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 
The Goulburn River at McCoys Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (9.00 m) during Monday and Tuesday. 
Renewed rises are likely from Wednesday as upstream floodwaters arrive.

McCoys Bridge is currently closed to all traffic.

The area north of Lords Road Buchanan Road up to Loch Garry Road is severely affected.
Following severe inundation you should avoid Bunbartha, Kaarimba and Mundoona areas.

Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon are around 30,000 ML/d and will remain around this flow for the next few days.

Forecast rainfall during Monday and Tuesday is expected to see renewed river level rises throughout the Goulburn River catchment, with prolonged or renewed minor to moderate flooding.

The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.


Updated Community information:

1. Illegal levees
In response to a number of concerns raised by community members, landowners are reminded that construction of works to divert the overland flow of water requires approval. To construct levees that interfere with overland water flows, without obtaining approval, is likely to impact on others and is also likely to be deemed illegal. 

We acknowledge these are difficult times for each impacted member of the community however, it is not appropriate to interfere with the natural overland flow of water as it can negatively impact on others. 


2. In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.

Many septic tanks have failed and floodwaters are contaminated.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases. 

Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.   

Do not camp or go bush driving close to rivers or creeks this long weekend.  

Unexpected river and creek levels are very likely even with small amounts of rain.   Support the local towns and make sure to set a watch zone for your location this long weekend and regularly check emergency radio broadcasters ( eg ABC radio) via your car radio if necessary.

Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.    

Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted area
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Review your emergency plan and check your emergency kit is fully stocked, if you have one. 
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
When returning home:
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  •  If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician.  
  •  For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/ Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
  •  Follow your emergency plan and locate your emergency kit, if you have one.
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety. 
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly.
  •  Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water.
  •  Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
Generators

If you are using a generator, do not attempt to connect it to the wiring of your home. This is dangerous and illegal.

A generator should only be used outside, with an extension cord to supply power direct to appliances such as the fridge or freezer. Using a generator indoors creates a number of safety risks including the potential for carbon monoxide poisoning or a fire. 
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Many local roads may still be closed and low bridges may still be underwater.
  • The Murray Valley Highway is fully closed at Mc Coys Bridge due to Bridge damage.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery: 
 Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: Register for clean up on private property; Navigating financial and other support Access to temporary accommodation Mental health and wellbeing support The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. 
  • Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  •  Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  •  Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  •  Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away   including canned and packaged foods. 
  •  It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.

properties.location: Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth.

MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE AT TALLANDOON DURING TUESDAY MORNING AND MCCALLUMS DURING MONDAY AFTERNOON River levels remain elevated along the Mitta Mitta River. 

At Tallandoon river level rises are being observed just below the minor flood level. 
Minor flooding is likely to develop from Monday afternoon, with moderate flooding possible from Tuesday morning.

River levels are rising along the Tallangatta Creek with minor flooding occurring and further rises likely during Monday.

In the 24 hours to 9:00 am 20-35 mm of rainfall totals have been observed across the catchment. Rainfall totals of 25-50mm have been forecast during Monday with higher isolated totals possible.
The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth:
Moderate flooding may occur along the Mitta Mitta River downstream of Lake Dartmouth.
The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is currently at 4.13 metres and rising. 
The Mitta Mitta River at Tallandoon is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.20 m) Monday afternoon. 
The river level may reach the moderate flood level (4.90 m) Tuesday morning with forecast rainfall.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Campaspe Barnadown to Rochester

Forecast rainfall over the next few days is likely to see renewed river level rises throughout the Campaspe River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear to be injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert    
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

  • If your buildings have been impacted by flood waters you should have your property inspected by a registered electrician. Visit the Energy Safe Victoria site for more: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/energy-safety-during-floods/
  • For more information on any assistance you need, visit emergency.vic.gov.au/relief/#relief_assistance
Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is for Barmah and Lower Moira .
  • An evacuation warning remains current. It is still not safe to return. Continue to avoid flood-affected areas.
  • Dangerous floodwater and widespread and significantly contaminated floodwater remain in several parts of the town.

  • Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.
  •  Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
  • To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.   
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.   

  • The Picola to Barmah Road is now open, however shallow water may still covers some parts of the road. 
  • The Nathalia relief centre is still open at the Nathalia Community Centre, 42 Robinson St, Nathalia operating 9-5, for after hours phone 0419717147.
It is not safe for people to return to Barmah and parts of Lower Moira.   
If you have not evacuated, you should now shelter in the highest location possible.
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.
What you should do:

  • Be aware of the increased likelihood of trees falling due to the very wet ground, especially in windy conditions. Never shelter under trees.  

If you have not already evacuated:
  • Stay where you are and shelter in the highest location possible.
  • Be aware that you may be isolated by floodwater for a significant amount of time.
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications - if you do not, phone Triple Zero (000) for assistance.
If you have already evacuated:
  • Do not return to your home until a Safe to Return notification is issued.
  • Register at a relief centre so that your friends, family and authorities can be informed that you are safe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.

This evacuation warning will remain in place until the area is declared safe to return.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flood levels may remain above floor level of a single-storey home.
  • Based on historic data, this flood has had a similar impact as the 1993 flood.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victor
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 02/11/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MURCHISON and SHEPPARTON
Moderate flooding may occur along the Goulburn River Seymour to Shepparton.

The Goulburn River at Murchison is currently at 9.41 metres and rising, with minor flooding. Renewed rises are likely in coming days as upstream floodwaters arrive and the Goulburn River at Murchison may reach around 9.90 metres during Tuesday, with minor flooding.

The Goulburn River at Shepparton is currently at 10.34 metres and steady, with minor flooding. Renewed rises are possible in coming days as upstream floodwaters arrive. The Goulburn River at Shepparton may reach the moderate flood level (10.70 m) during Wednesday.

Goulburn Murray Water has advised that releases from Lake Eildon are around 30,000 ML/d and will remain around this flow for the next few days.

Forecast rainfall during Monday and Tuesday is expected to see renewed river level rises throughout the Goulburn River catchment, with prolonged or renewed minor to moderate flooding.

  • Please note that Regional Roads Victoria have advised that the Murchison Bridge on the Murchison-Violet Town Road (High Road) is open to light vehicles only. NO TRUCKS OR HEAVY AGRICULTURE MACHINERY.  

Updated Community Information: 
  • Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.
  • Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.
  • In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.   

Do not to camp close to rivers or creeks.     

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon.   

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
  • If cleaning after damage has occurred, protect your health and safety.
  • Protect your lungs by wearing a N95 or P2 mask. 
  • Wear strong boots, gloves and protective clothing and wash your hands and clothes regularly. 
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
If returning home
  • Only turn your power on at the main electrical switchboard if water has not entered the property. 
  • If water has entered your property, do not put the power back on until the property wiring has been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • If any appliances have been inundated, do not plug them in or switch them on until they have been tested by a licensed electrician. 
  • For more information visit: https://esv.vic.gov.au/safety-education/emergencies/electrical-emergency/
Impacts in your area: 

  • Smelly black water can be reported to EPA on 1800 560 760
  • Stagnant water can be harmful to your health. Donâ€™t swim, drink or wash in stagnant water. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Local roads may be closed and low bridges may be underwater.
  • Please note that Regional Roads Victoria have advised that the Murchison Bridge on the Murchison-Violet Town Road (High Road) is open to light vehicles only. NO TRUCKS OR HEAVY AGRICULTURE MACHINERY. 
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Don't go fishing, kayaking, or boating. Floodwaters is dangerous due to debris, submerged trees and other hidden dangers. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 12:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support
  • Access to temporary accommodation 
  • Mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Health Messaging
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  • Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  • Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  • Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  • Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick. 
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. 
  • Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal. 
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away, including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077.

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning is being issued for parts of Echuca and Echuca Village. 
If you live, work or are holidaying in this area, you should Evacuate Immediately. 

MAJOR FLOODING AT ECHUCA AND MOAMA PEAKED AT 94.98 METRES AHD WEDNESDAY NIGHT, HIGHER THAN THE 1975 AND 1993 FLOODS

Along the Murray River the river level at Echuca and Moama peaked around 94.98 metres AHD Wednesday night 26 October with major flooding, higher than the October 1993 (94.77 m AHD) and November 1975 (94.80 m AHD) flood peaks.

MURRAY RIVER
  • The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD on Wednesday 26 October and is currently at 94.84 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Echuca may remain above the major flood level (94.40 metres AHD) until 05-06 November.
CAMPASPE RIVER
  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The Campaspe River at Echuca is currently at 94.58 m AHD (Australian Height Datum) and steady, with moderate flooding. The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday. 
  • River levels will remain elevated due to floodwaters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days.
For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: The NSW State Emergency Service have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
If you are located in the warning areas, it is recommended you Evacuate Immediately. If you do not relocate now you may become isolated for a number of days. If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you. 

The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium located at 244 High street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
What you should do: 

Travel to a safe location. Options include: 
  • Travel to family and friends outside of the impacted area.
  • The Echuca Emergency Relief Centre (Echuca South Basketball Stadium located at 244 High Street, Echuca) can be accessed by people if required.
  • The recommended evacuation route is via High Street Echuca
If you are travelling by car: 
  • Do not drive through floodwater. 
  • Find alternative travel routes if roads or underpasses are flooded. 
  • Be aware of driving hazards, such as mud, debris, damaged roads and fallen trees. 
  • If driving conditions are dangerous, safely pull over away from trees, drains, low lying areas and floodwater. 
If you stay:  
  • Stay inside and be aware of changing conditions. 
  • If floodwater comes inside, move to a higher point such as a kitchen bench or second story. 
  • Follow your emergency plan, if you have one. 
  • Contact family members and neighbours to ensure they are aware of the situation, if safe to do so. 
  • If you choose to stay, emergency services may not be able to help you.
  • Flood water is impacting sewerage systems in Echuca. Residents should limit water usage where possible-this will reduce the volume being sent to sewerage while flood levels are high.
  • Most levees are not designed for the level of flooding we are currently experiencing, so there are risks of overtopping and potential for breach or failure.
  • We urge the community to avoid being on or near the levee in Echuca township to reduce the risk of erosion and/or damage to the levee.
You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. Call Triple Zero (000) in a life threatening emergency. 

For emergency assistance from the SES, call 132 500.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Echuca village residents, if you do not relocate now you could become isolated for 10-15 days.
  • Evacuating too late or choosing to remain in your home when recommended to evacuate, is dangerous and may put your life at risk. 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur. 
  • Areas near the affected location may lose services including power, water, sewerage and phone coverage due to flooding.
  • We are aware of discolouration in the tap water in parts of Echuca. We have confirmed the issues is the result of increased Manganese levels in the water supply, and a treatment plan for this issue is in place. Elevated Manganese levels in the water do NOT pose a risk to your health when used for drinking, bathing, cooking or cleaning. We are continuing to monitor raw water quality.
  • To prevent the sewer network being overwhelmed, we are asking all Echuca residents to minimise their use of anything that produces wastewater, including toilets, showers, baths, dishwashers and washing machines.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes. Leave all uninjured wildlife alone and they are likely to be fatigued and stressed. If you see animals that appear to be injured or caught in floodwater, call 136 186 or advise via the wildlife emergency app.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
  • For assistance call the Flood Recovery Hotline at 1800560760.
Mosquito Alert 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease. 
What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.  
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin. 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 06:00 pm or as the situation changes. 

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria. 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

This Flood Watch is being issued for Bemm, Cann and Genoa Rivers.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.

In parts of the North East and far East Gippsland, isolated major flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday. Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.

Catchments likely to be affected include:

Bemm, Cann and Genoa Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:

properties.name: Emergency Warning
properties.webBody:
This Emergency Warning - Not Safe to Return is being issued for Bogong Village.

  • An evacuation warning remains current. It is not safe to return.

  • There is a large active slow moving landslide on the Bogong High Plains Road in the area near Spring Saddle Track above Bogong Village

  • Bogong High Plains Road to Falls Creek from Mount Beauty is closed to all traffic. It is expected to be closed for some time.
It is not safe for people to return to Bogong Village. Stay away from the landslide.
What you should do:
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Stay away from the landslide - the slope may continue to move for weeks afterwards.

If you become trapped under debris:
  • Do not light a match.
  • Stay as still as possible and cover your mouth with a handkerchief or clothing.
  • Tap on a pipe or wall so rescuers can locate you. Shout only as a last resort.

Inside:
  • If you are inside and a landslide occurs, find cover in the section of the building that is furthest away from the approaching landslide and take shelter under a table or bench.

Driving:
  • The Bogong High Plains Road is closed between Mount Beauty and Falls Creek for all traffic.
  • Plan your trip in advance - travel may take longer due to closed roads and poor driving conditions.
Outdoors:
  • If you are outside and a landslide occurs, move quickly away from the likely path, keeping clear of embankments, trees, power lines and poles.
  • Stay away from the landslide - the slope may experience additional failures for hours to days afterwards.
Impacts in your area:
The landslide has resulted in:
  • Fallen trees and branches.
  • Dangerous road conditions.
  • Mud and debris on the road
This message was issued by Department of Environment, Land, Water & Planning.

The next update is expected by 07/11/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Advice is being issued for Loddon River downstream of Kerang.

River levels are elevated along the Loddon River downstream of Kerang.

  • Flooding from the Murray River and Loddon River is impacting buildings and roads in the Murrabit West area. These include Salau Road, Dawe Road, Henry Lane, Flowerday Lane and sections of Murrabit West Road.
  • Buildings, farm land and roads in the Benjeroop area have also been impacted and will continue to be closely monitored.
  • Cohuna Golf Links area is currently stable with no expected rises. 
  • Catchments where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and flooding is possible from early next week at some locations.
Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause renewed river rises across the Loddon River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
  • Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Updated community newsletters are available for locals in Gannawarra Shire Council and Swan Hill Rural City Council areas to answer any questions you may have.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 07:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app

  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Barham to Wentworth.

River levels at Swan Hill and downstream are likely to be similar to the 1993 event. Forecasts will be progressively refined once the upstream flood peaks along the Murray River and its tributaries are observed.

  • The Murray River at Swan Hill is likely to exceed the minor flood level (4.50m) during Monday. The river may reach the major flood level (4.70m) during the second week of November (8 to 11 November). 
  • The Murray River at Wakool Junction may reach around 11.40m 20 to 23 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Boundary Bend may exceed the moderate flood level (8.50m) Sunday evening. The river level may reach around 8.70 metres 24 to 26 November, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Euston may exceed the minor flood level (9.10m) in mid November. The river level may reach around 9.50m 25 to 27 November, with minor flooding.
  • The Murray River at Mildura Weir may exceed the minor flood level (36.00 metres AHD) around 10 to 12 November. The river level may reach 37.50m AHD round the end of November, with moderate flooding, similar to the 1993 flood.
Further rainfall is forecast during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.

Water quality update:
People may notice a slight discolouration in their water over the coming weeks due to blackwater within the Murray River. Please be assured that your urban water remains safe to drink and is tested to comply with Australian Drinking Water standards. Blackwater is the discolouration of water in the river, which is caused by high levels of tannins from organic material like fallen leaves and bark and from trees and undergrowth. Lower Murray Water is continuing to monitor and fine tune the treatment processes at our water treatment plants to reduce any clarity and taste impacts associated with treating black water. 

Community meetings are being held over the coming week for residents in Swan Hill, Robinvale and Mildura.
  • Monday 31 October 6.30pm - Swan Hill Town Hall
  • Wednesday 2 November 6.30pm - Robinvale Community Arts Centre 
  • Sunday 6 November 4pm - Mildura Sporting Precinct 
An updated Community Newsletter is available that has answers to some of your questions from Monday night's community meeting at Swan Hill, information about how to report levee issues and a link to the online interactive map, which shows the estimated 1993 flood extent.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels online by visiting www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings website.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnâ€™t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Forecasts for Swan Hill and downstream will be progressively refined once the upstream flood peaks along the Murray River and its tributaries are observed.
  • Further rainfall is forecast during Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.
  • High river levels may cause flooding in areas close to rivers and streams and local roads may be closed.
  • Some agricultural land may be vulnerable to flooding. Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area please check https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/ in New South Wales and https://www.emergency.vic.gov.au/ in Victoria.
Murray River closure:
The Murray River is closed to river craft downstream of Tocumwal Bridge to Robinvale. People and boats are prohibited from entering the river between these locations. Any person on the Murray between these points are to leave the river. This declaration applies to all residents on both sides of the border. Neither NSW or Victorian users are permitted on the river at this time.

Blackwater and blue green algae:  
  • Significant rainfall and flooding can cause water quality issues like low-oxygen (hypoxic) blackwater and blue green algae. 
  • High levels of organic matter have been washed into waterways and, combined with warm weather, can cause oxygen levels in the water to drop. This can harm or cause the death of fish and crayfish. Any fish death event in Victoria should be reported to the EPA by calling 1300 372 842.
  • River managers and scientists monitor rivers for water quality issues and work to reduce the impacts of a blackwater event where they can. 
  • Low levels of dissolved oxygen are recorded at several locations across northern Victoria and in the Murray River. The scale of the current flooding means water quality will not improve quickly. 
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 05:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford.

The Yarra River catchment has recorded rainfall averaging about 1 mm in the upper part of the catchment and about 1 mm in the lower part of the catchment since 09:00 AM Sunday 30 October 2022. Rainfall totals of 10-20 mm are forecast for the catchment on Monday 31 October 2022, with thunderstorms and isolated totals of 30-40 mm possible.

Yarra River from Warrandyte to Abbotsford:

The level of the Yarra River at Templestowe is currently at 4.49 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.50 metres), and falling. It peaked at 5.24 metres around 8:15 AM on Sunday 30 October 2022 and is expected to drop below Minor Flood Level (3.50 metres) on Friday 4 November 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Heidelberg is currently at 7.93 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres), and falling. It peaked at 8.22 metres, just below the Moderate Flood Level (8.30 metres), around 8:30 AM on Sunday 30 October 2022 and is expected to drop below Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) on Saturday 5 November 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Alphington is currently at 4.76 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (3.00 metres), and falling. It peaked at 5.03 metres, below the Moderate Flood Level (6.00 metres), around 2:00 PM on Sunday 30 October 2022 and is expected to drop below Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) on Sunday 6 November 2022.

The level of the Yarra River at Abbotsford is currently at 4.69 metres, exceeding the Minor Flood Level (2.70 metres), and falling. It peaked at 4.95 metres, below the Moderate Flood Level (6.70 metres), around 8:00 PM on Sunday 30 October 2022 and is expected to drop below Minor Flood Level (6.00 metres) on Saturday 5 November 2022.

Minor to Moderate flooding in the Yarra/Watts River catchments is causing substantial inundation in rural and/or urban areas, and disruption to traffic. Melba Highway at Yarra Glen is expected to get flooded. 

  • This is an update, replacing the Advice message issued at 9:00 PM on the 30/10/2022.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
Impacts in your area: 

  • Minor flooding in the Yarra River catchment is affecting low-lying areas adjacent to the waterway including bicycle paths.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.

This Flood Watch is being issued for South Gippsland Rivers.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water. 

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon.

Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.

In parts of the East Gippsland, isolated flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday.

Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.

Catchment likely to be affected include:

South Gippsland Rivers
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility:
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency.
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Avoca River downstream of Charlton.

  • Minor flooding has eased at Downstream Charlton Town. Minor flooding is easing at Quambatook.
  • The Avoca River at Quambatook peaked at 2.19m around 10:00am Sunday 30 October and is currently at 2.06m and falling, with minor flooding. The Avoca River at Quambatook is likely to fall below the minor flood level (2.00m) Monday evening.
In the 24 hours to 12:00 pm Monday, rainfall totals of less than 5 mm were recorded in the Avoca River catchment. Forecast rainfall over the next few days is likely to see renewed river level rises across the Avoca River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area, monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
Impacts in your area: 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.location: Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Loddon River Loddon Weir to Kerang.

Minor to moderate flooding is continuing along the Loddon River with Moderate flooding is occurring Downstream Loddon Weir and Kerang.

  • The Loddon River at Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir is currently at 5.92m and rising, with minor flooding.
  • The Loddon River at Appin South is currently peaking around 3.16m, with moderate flooding. The Loddon River at Appin South is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.10m) for the next few days.
  • The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is currently at 77.33m Australian Height Datum (AHD) and steady, with minor flooding. The Loddon River at MV Hwy Bridge is expected to remain above the minor flood level (77.00m) for the next few days. Further rises are likely as upstream peaks arrive.
Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause renewed river rises across the Loddon River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Check you have enough food, drinking water and medications.
  • Rising floodwater can be dangerous. Be aware of water levels rising near you.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - do not drive through floodwater. Do not overestimate the capability of your vehicle. It doesnâ€™t take much to make your car become unstable, lose traction or wash away.
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
Community newsletter 
A community newsletter for Gannawarra Shire has been developed to assist with any questions locals may have. Go to: Community Newsletter - Gannawarra Shire.
Impacts in your area:
  • A number of local and arterial roads are closed due to floodwater. For more information on road closures go to VicTraffic. 
  • Some areas are likely to lose services including power, water, sewerage and telephone due to flooding.
  • Be aware that snakes may look for shelter and food inside houses, storage sheds and other buildings near floodwater. Damaged structures and debris are more accessible to snakes.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 07:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

MODERATE FLOODING MAY DEVELOP AT BANDIANA DURING MONDAY EVENING
MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MONGANS BRIDGE, KIEWA MAIN STREAM AND BANDIANA 

Minor flooding is continuing along the Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) and Bandiana, with renewed minor flooding occurring at Mongans Bridge. 
Moderate flooding is possible along the Kiewa River from Monday evening.
Further rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday, with renewed river level rises likely. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge:
Moderate flooding may occur along the Kiewa River downstream of Mongans Bridge.

The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is currently at 3.40 metres and steady, with minor flooding. 
The Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) is expected to remain above the minor flood level (3.30 m) during Monday. 
Renewed rises are likely during Tuesday with forecast rainfall.

The Kiewa River at Bandiana is currently at 3.07 metres and rising, with minor flooding. The Kiewa River at Bandiana may reach the moderate flood level (3.10 m) Monday evening. Further rises above the moderate flood level are possible with forecast rainfall.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides â€“ be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Watch is being issued for Yea River, King Parrot Creek & Sunday Creek.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.
Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due to recent rainfall. 
Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.
Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 
Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.
Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.

Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. 
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  
Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.  
What you should do:
The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning.  If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree. 

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks. 

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall and ongoing water releases from Lake Eildon. 

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater. In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers & streams may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 03:00 pm or as the situation changes.

  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.
Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. 
Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.
Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall.


Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. 

Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.

Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.  
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. 
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  
Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.

This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Broken Creek at Walshs Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING TO CONTINUE ALONG THE BROKEN CREEK AT WALSHS BRIDGE AND NATHALIA FOR THE NEXT FEW DAYS WITH RENEWED RISES LIKELY FROM WEDNESDAY

Minor flooding is expected to continue for the next few days between Walshs Bridge and Nathalia, with further rainfall during Monday night and Tuesday likely to cause renewed rises and prolong the minor flooding. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary. 

The Broken Creek at Nathalia is currently at 2.24 metres and steady with minor flooding. The Broken Creek at Nathalia is expected to remain around its current level for the next few days with renewed rises likely later in the week from forecast rainfall.
Minor flooding is occurring along the Broken Creek. 


Updated community information: 
 Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.

Be aware that mosquito borne disease hazards are present so please cover up and use repellent.

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick. 

To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water. 
Avoid contact with Flood waters to prevent illness. 

Flood waters may contain sewerage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewerage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas.

The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning. 

If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly. Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree. 

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary. 

What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 04:00 pm or as the situation changes.

properties.webBody:
This Flood Advice is being issued in the lower Bendigo and Bullock Creeks.

  • Flooding is occurring in the lower Bendigo and Bullock Creeks. 
  • Increased flows from Kow Swamp into Pyramid Creek continue to create significant impacts for downstream areas. Flood waters may continue to impact properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang over the coming days.
  • Residents in properties along the Pyramid Creek from Kow Swamp to Kerang should expect to see increased water levels below Milnes Bridge and further to the Kerang-Koondrook Road, with some levees being overtopped leading to potential breaches.
Widespread showers and storms are expected for Monday and Tuesday. Rapid river level rises and localised flooding is possible in areas of heavier rainfall. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do: 
  • People living or working along rivers and streams must monitor the latest weather forecasts and warnings and be ready to move to higher ground should flooding develop.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
Mosquito alert:
The risk of mosquito breeding is high. You can reduce your risk of being bitten and getting sick:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible.
  • Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease
An updated community newsletter is available for locals in the Gannawarra Shire Council area to answer any questions you may have.
Impacts in your area
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home may occur in some locations.
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Check the VicTraffic website for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service 

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 02:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.location: Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham
properties.webBody:
This Major Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham. 

Murray River downstream of Tocumwal to Barham:

  • Major flooding is occurring at Echuca, Moama, Torrumbarry and Barham.
  • The Murray River at Echuca peaked at 94.98 metres AHD on Wednesday 26 October and is currently at 94.84 metres AHD and falling slowly, with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir is currently at 7.83 metres and peaking, with major flooding. The Murray River at Torrumbarry Weir may remain around 7.85 metres until 4-6 November with major flooding.
  • The Murray River at Barham is currently at 6.17 metres and falling slowly, with major flooding. The Murray River at Barham may remain above the major flood level (6.10 metres) until 10-12 November.

There is an Emergency Warning Not Safe to Return in place for Barmah and Lower Moira.

There is an Evacuation Warning in place for Echuca and Echuca Village.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Move to higher ground. Act now - immediately take actions to protect your life and property.

All public land including state and national parks, forests and reserves along the Murray downstream of Tocumwal to Barham are closed. If you are currently in these areas please be advised of the severe weather and thunderstorm warnings in place. Be aware that soft ground, erosion of roots and potential high winds can cause falling trees.

For your safety, you are strongly encouraged to pack up and leave as soon as possible.




What you should do: 
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater. 
  • Decide if you will evacuate if it becomes necessary.
  • For commercial and recreational users of the Murray River: NSW State Emergency Services have declared an emergency area on the Murray River for areas downstream of Tocumal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge under the state Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act). Do not enter the emergency area. This applies to all commercial and recreational users. Visit the NSW SES website for information: https://www.ses.nsw.gov.au/news/all-news/2022/emergency-area-declared-murray-river/
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
If you choose to leave: 
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications. 
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding. 
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave. 
If you are travelling: 
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around and find a safe alternative route. 
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.   
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave: 
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated. 
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow. 
  • Stay informed - listen to emergency broadcasters and monitor warnings.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in many locations. 
  • Main roads and bridges may be closed due to flooding.
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone as they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear injured or caught in flood water, call 136186 or via the Wildlife Emergency App
This message was issued by State Emergency Service. 

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed: 
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au 
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226 
  • VicEmergency app 
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods) 
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV. 
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.   
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
