This Flood Watch is being issued for Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie.

MODERATE FLOODING CONTINUING AT APPIN SOUTH 

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LAANECOORIE, DOWNSTREAM (D/S) LODDON WEIR AND KERANG 

Minor to moderate flooding is continuing along the Loddon River. Moderate flooding is occurring at Appin South. Minor flooding is occurring at Downstream (D/S) Laanecoorie, Downstream (D/S) Loddon Weir and Kerang. 

Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause renewed river rises across the Loddon River catchment. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary .

Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie:

Renewed river rises are expected along the Loddon River upstream of Laanecoorie and along the Bet Bet Creek. 

The Loddon River D/S Cairn Curran is currently at 1.82 metres and steady, below the minor flood level. 

The Loddon River D/S Cairn Curran is likely to remain below the minor flood level (2.00 m) during Monday.

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert.
What you should do:
  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • Decide what you and your family will do if flooding impacts you. For information on how to prepare go to www.ses.vic.gov.au/get-ready/floodsafe
  • Floodwater is toxic - never play or swim in floodwater.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings. 
  • Check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au for information on road closures.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • Be aware of the risk of mosquitos bring and cover up with long, loose-fitting clothing.
Impacts in your area: 
  • Areas around rivers and streams may be flooded.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 31/10/2022 07:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert: 
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease.

What you can do:
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing 
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin or DEET 
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens.
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 

Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with:
  • navigating available supports
  • clean-up
  • temporary accommodation
  • mental health and wellbeing support
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday.

Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9.
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods
If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.webBody:
This Minor Flood Warning is being issued for Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal.

Flood operations are being conducted by the Murray-Darling Basin Authority (MDBA) at Hume Dam to manage inflows from the upper Murray, Mitta Mitta River and other tributaries. MDBA are working closely with the Bureau and WaterNSW to plan release strategies.

As at 1600hrs today, 48,992 ML/Day is being released from Hume Dam.

Further rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday, which may cause renewed river level rises and flooding. The situation is being closely monitored and revised predictions will be provided if necessary.


Murray River downstream of Hume Dam to Tocumwal:
  • Moderate flooding is possible at Albury, Yarrawonga, and Tocumwal. Moderate flooding is occurring at Corowa.
  • The Murray River at Albury may reach the moderate flood level (4.90 metres) overnight Monday into Tuesday. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Corowa may reach near 6.50 metres around Wednesday, with moderate flooding.
  • The Murray River at Yarrawonga Downstream gauge may reach the moderate flood level (6.70 metres) late this week. Further rises are possible.
  • The Murray River at Tocumwal may exceed the minor flood level (6.40 metres) late Monday. Further rises to the moderate flood level (6.70 metres) are possible late this week. 
NSW SES Declaration of Emergency Area 

  • The NSW State Emergency Service have declared the following areas of the Murray River are an emergency area under the State Emergency Services Act 1989 (NSW) (SES Act):
    • Downstream of Tocumwal Road Bridge to Barham Bridge. 
    •  Murray River from the Tocumwal Road Bridge to Tooleybuc Bridge 
    Under section 22 of the SES Act people are directed as follows: 
    • Leave the emergency area. 
    • Do not enter the emergency area. 
    This applies to all commercial and recreational users of the rivers. No boats can enter the emergency area and people cannot enter the area for any recreational purpose such as fishing or swimming.

Updated Community Information: 

Please find here the YouTube link for the Community Update from the Cobram community meeting recorded Saturday and is still relevant over the next few days.  To watch the link to Community Update on YouTube click on or follow this link: https://youtu.be/rJqfiT3yCC4

 Do not put Lithium-ion batteries in with general rubbish. Dispose of via a municipal battery collection facility.  Damaged or defective batteries can overheat, catch fire or explode releasing projectiles and can release toxic gases.

In flood-affected areas, there are now many cases of gastro (gastroenteritis, diarrhoea) causing people to get very sick.   
To prevent gastro always wash your hands after going to the toilet, before eating, preparing food, or cleaning your teeth etc. Only drink and wash, or wash clothes in known clean water.    
Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home.  
Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 

The wet ground conditions have resulted in many trees falling without warning. If it gets windy, trees will become more unstable and deadly.  Never park, take shelter or camp under a tree.    

Do not camp close to rivers or creeks.     

Unexpected river rises are very likely after even small amounts of rainfall.  

Stay informed - monitor your local conditions and remain alert. Never enter floodwater.   

In the VicEmergency App, add a watch zone for your campsite and regularly check emergency broadcasters via car radio if necessary.
What you should do: 

  • Be prepared to act if your situation changes.
  • You should stay informed by listening to emergency broadcasters and monitoring warnings.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
  • Consequences of flooding along the Murray River will vary between NSW and Victoria. For more information relevant to your area, please check: www.ses.nsw.gov.au in NSW and www.emergency.vic.gov.au in Victoria.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
Impacts in your area: 

  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • For more information on road closures check the VicRoads website traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au.
  • Caravan parks and camping grounds may be flooded.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 05:30 pm or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
  • For road closure information go to www.traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au or phone 13 11 70.
  • For health information and support contact the below organisations: Lifeline on www.lifeline.org.au or phone 13 11 14. Beyond Blue on www.beyondblue.org.au or phone 1300 224 636. Kids Helpine on www.kidshelp.com.au or phone 1800 551 800. SANE Australia on www.sane.org or phone 1800 187 263.
Accessibility: 
The following services can help you, or someone you know, access information during an emergency. 
  • To access this information in other languages call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline. 
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.  

Health Messaging 
  • Avoid contact with floodwaters to prevent illness. 
  • Floodwaters may contain sewage and other toxic waste and can also overflow into your home. Contact with sewage can make people sick, so clean and disinfect any impacted areas. 
  •  Stay out of the water - skin contact with floodwater or mud can cause illness and skin infections. Cover cuts and if you are injured during your clean up; clean the wound and contact your doctor immediately.  
  •  Private water supplies may also be contaminated from floodwater, debris and chemicals. If your water supply tastes, looks or smells unusual, do not use it for drinking, preparing food, and do not give it to animals.  
  •  Medicines, stored at home and affected by flood water may now be unsafe and extreme caution should be taken in trying to salvage any medicines. 
  • Mosquitoes can also breed rapidly in stagnant waters. Drain any water from containers such as plant pots, tyres, buckets, and roof gutters to control mosquitos around your home. 
  •  Flooding can also cause excessive mould growth which must be cleaned up before moving back to your home as it can make you sick.
  • Any damaged gas or electricity supplies need to be declared safe by a qualified electrician or plumber. Do not use a portable generator indoors, they can produce carbon monoxide gas which could build up in a confined space and make you sick or be fatal.
  • Food safety should also be considered and ALL food that has been flood damaged should be thrown away - including canned and packaged foods. 
  • It is important to look after your mental health and that of friends, family and neighbours. If at any time you are worried about your mental health or the mental health of a loved one, call Lifeline 13 11 14 or the Suicide Call Back Service on 1300 659 467.
Recovery:
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  • Register for clean up on private property; 
  • Navigating financial and other support;
  • Access to temporary accommodation;
  • Mental health and wellbeing support.

The recovery hotline is open from 7:30am-7:30pm everyday.   Call 1800 560 760 or visit www.erv.vic.gov.au for further information. 

For life-threatening emergencies, call Triple Zero (000) immediately. 
For emergency assistance during floods call 132 500 for SES assistance.

Register Find Unite - Red Cross 
Red Cross has opened Register.Find.Reunite. and is urging people affected by the Victorian Floods to get in touch with their families and friends. Register.Find.Reunite. helps find and reunite family, friends and loved ones during a disaster. People can register on the Red Cross website at register.redcross.org.au, or by phone at 1800 727 077. 

This is a community message to advise the community not to build own levees as it changes the flow of the water and impacting other properties.

This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge.

MINOR FLOODING OCCURRING AT MONGANS BRIDGE, KIEWA MAIN STREAM AND BANDIANA Minor flooding is continuing along the Kiewa River at Kiewa (Main Stream) and Bandiana, with renewed minor flooding occurring at Mongans Bridge. Moderate flooding is possible along the Kiewa River from Monday evening.

Further rainfall is forecast for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday, with renewed river level rises likely. The situation is being closely monitored, and warnings will be updated as necessary.

Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge:
Minor flooding is occurring at Mongans Bridge. The Kiewa River at Mongans Bridge is currently at 2.68 metres and rising, with minor flooding. Further rises are likely along the Kiewa River to Mongans Bridge with forecast rainfall during Monday and areas of moderate flooding may develop overnight.

Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater. 
  • Farmers should move livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations.
  • Heavy rainfall may lead to an increased risk of landslides â€“ be aware of fallen earth, rocks, debris or trees.

This Flood Watch is being issued for TAMBO RIVER.

WIDESPREAD RENEWED RIVER RISES AND MINOR TO MODERATE FLOODING POSSIBLE FROM MONDAY AFTERNOON 

A low pressure system approaching western Bass Strait is extending a cold front across Victoria during Monday. The low will dive south of Tasmania later today as the front clears to the east, followed by a low pressure trough crossing the state on Tuesday.

Widespread showers and storms are expected for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday.

Catchments in the flood watch area are saturated, some of which are experiencing ongoing flooding due torecent rainfall. Storages are mostly at or near capacity and spilling or actively releasing water.

Widespread renewed river level rises are likely and minor flooding may develop in the flood watch area from Monday afternoon. Catchments with recent or existing warnings where river levels are elevated may see fast response to further rainfall and moderate flooding is possible at some locations.

In parts of the North East and far East Gippsland, isolated major flooding is possible in small and fast responding catchments from late Monday into Tuesday..

Catchment likely to be affected include:

TAMBO RIVER

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the King River.

MODERATE FLOODING OCCURRING AT WANGARATTA AND DOCKER RD BRIDGE RENEWED FLOODING IS LIKELY IN THE OVENS AND KING RIVERS FROM MIDDAY MONDAY 

Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River at Docker Road Bridge and has extended along the Ovens River at Wangaratta. 
Minor flooding is occurring along the King River at Downstream (D/S) Lake William Hovell, and the Ovens River at Rocky Point. 

Renewed river rises are occurring along parts of the Ovens and King rivers and renewed flooding is likely from Monday evening.
Renewed minor flooding is expected along the Buffalo River at Downstream (D/S) Lake Buffalo from early Monday evening.

Forecast rainfall for the remainder of Monday and Tuesday is likely to cause further river level rises and prolong the duration of flooding through out the Ovens and King catchments. 

King River:
Moderate flooding is occurring along the King River.
The King River D/S Lake William Hovell is currently at 1.79 metres and steady, around the minor flood level.
The King River D/S Lake William Hovell may remain around the minor flood level (1.80 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday. The King River at Docker Rd Bridge peaked at 4.06 metres around Saturday afternoon and is currently at 3.98 metres and steady, with moderate flooding. Renewed river level rises are expected along the King River at Docker Rd Bridge from early Monday evening. The river level is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (3.95 m) overnight Monday into Tuesday.
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater. 
What you should do:
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Farmers should consider moving livestock and machinery to higher ground.
  • If you are camping close to a creek or river, you may be at risk of flooding and need to move to higher ground, away from waterways.
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/

If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams.
  • Low lying agricultural areas may be flooded
  • The Docker-Carbour Road is closed between Wangaratta-Whitfield Road and Oxley-Meadow Creek Road.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 02/11/2022 11:30 am or as the situation changes.

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.

  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.

properties.name: Watch & Act
properties.webBody:
This Moderate Flood Warning is being issued for the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester.

  • Moderate flooding is occurring along the Campaspe River downstream of Rochester. 
  • The Campaspe River at Echuca is currently at 94.58 m AHD (Australian Height Datum) and steady, with moderate flooding. The river is expected to remain above the moderate flood level (94.40 m AHD) for the remainder of Monday and into Tuesday. 
  • River levels will remain elevated due to floodwaters backing up from the Murray River and are expected to continue in the coming days. 

The latest community newsletter from Saturday 29 October is available here: Community Newsletter
Stay safe - avoid the flooded area. Be aware of potential hazards caused by flooding and never enter floodwater.
  
What you should do:

  • Floodwater is dangerous - never enter floodwater.
  • Check the VicTraffic website (traffic.vicroads.vic.gov.au) for road closures and follow instructions from emergency services. 
  • Monitor weather forecasts and river levels. Go to www.bom.gov.au/vic/warnings/
If you choose to leave:
  • Remember to take your pets, mobile phone, spare clothes and medications.
  • Travel to the home of family or friends who are in a safe location, away from flooding.
  • Turn off gas and electricity at your home or workplace.
  • Be aware of any road closures when you leave.
If you are travelling:
  • Do not enter flooded areas. Turn around a find a safe alternative route.
  • Be aware of road hazards including mud, debris and damaged roads or bridges.
  • Floodwater is dangerous - never drive, walk or ride through floodwater.
If you stay or if it is unsafe to leave:
  • Make sure you have enough food, drinking water, medications and pet food to survive for three to five days in case you become isolated.
  • Use plugs, sandbags or household items to block toilets, sinks and drains to stop sewerage backflow.
  • Lift it - move valuables and vital household items up on high surfaces, such as on top of tables, chairs, benches and beds.
Impacts in your area:
  • Flooding above floor level of a single-story home is likely to occur in some locations. 
  • High river levels and potential flooding in areas close to rivers and streams. 
  • You may see animals attempting to move to higher ground, including snakes.
  • Leave all uninjured wildlife alone as they are likely to be fatigued and stressed.
  • If you see animals that appear injured or caught in flood water, call 136186 or via the Wildlife Emergency App.
This message was issued by State Emergency Service.

The next update is expected by 01/11/2022 01:00 pm or as the situation changes.

Mosquito Alert     
With the recent floods in many areas across Victoria, the risk of mosquito breeding is high. Learn more about how to protect yourself and your family at https://www.betterhealth.vic.gov.au/protect-yourself-mosquito-borne-disease.  
What you can do: 
  • Cover up - wear long, loose-fitting clothing.   
  • Use repellents that contain picaridin.  
  • Use mosquito nets or insect screens. 
  • Limit activity outdoors and move indoors if possible. 
Flood Recovery Hotline - Call 1800 560 760 
Flood Recovery Hotline is a single state-wide number, 1800 560 760, that Victorians impacted by the October 2022 floods can call for help or assistance with: 
  •  navigating available supports clean-up
  •  temporary accommodation 
  •  mental health and wellbeing support 
The recovery hotline is open from 7.30am-7.30pm everyday. 
Need an interpreter? Call the hotline on 1800 560 760 and press 9. 
For flood and storm information and support in NSW visit nsw.gov.au/floods   

If you require assistance relating to insurance matters, please call the Insurance Council Australia's disaster hotline on 1800 734 621.   

For local flood risk information: 
  • North Central CMA: nccma.vic.gov.au/floodplain-management 
  • VICSES Flood Guides: https://www.ses.vic.gov.au/plan-and-stay-safe/flood-guides/campaspe-shire-council 
  • Campaspe Shire Council: https://www.campaspe.vic.gov.au/Our-services/Emergency-management/Flood-event-2022

Use multiple sources to stay informed:
  • www.emergency.vic.gov.au
  • VicEmergency Hotline - freecall 1800 226 226
  • VicEmergency app
  • Facebook or Twitter (#vicfloods)
  • Tune in to ABC Local Radio, commercial and designated community radio stations, or Sky News TV.
Accessibility:

  • To access this information in other languages, call the Translating and Interpreting Service on 131 450 (freecall) and ask them to call VicEmergency Hotline.
  • If you are deaf, hard of hearing, or have a speech/communication impairment contact National Relay Service on 1800 555 677 and ask them to call the VicEmergency Hotline.
